1. Introduction
1.1 Project Overview
This project focuses on predicting the temperature of an electric motor using machine learning techniques. Electric motors are widely used in industrial systems, electric vehicles, and manufacturing equipment. Monitoring motor temperature is crucial because excessive heat can lead to reduced efficiency, component damage, and system failure.
In this project, a machine learning model is developed to predict the temperature of a motorís permanent magnet surface using various operational parameters such as voltage, torque, speed, and current.
The system analyzes sensor data collected from motors and uses regression algorithms to estimate temperature in real time. By converting raw sensor data into meaningful predictions, the system helps identify overheating risks early and supports predictive maintenance.
Key objectives include:
* Predict motor temperature using machine learning models.
* Analyze relationships between motor operational features and temperature.
* Identify patterns indicating overheating conditions.
* Deploy a model that can provide real-time predictions through a web interface.

1.2 Purpose
The purpose of this project is to develop a predictive system that can estimate motor temperature using machine learning models.
Instead of relying only on traditional monitoring methods, this system leverages historical sensor data to detect patterns and predict future temperature values.
This approach helps:
* Engineers monitor motor performance.
* Prevent overheating and equipment failure.
* Improve predictive maintenance strategies.
* Reduce maintenance costs and downtime.

2. Ideation Phase
2.1 Problem Statement
Electric motors play a critical role in many industrial systems and machines. However, excessive temperature can reduce motor efficiency, damage components, and lead to system failure.
Traditional monitoring methods rely on threshold-based alarms that react only after overheating occurs. This reactive approach may lead to delayed intervention and costly failures.
This project aims to develop a machine learning model that predicts motor temperature based on sensor data such as speed, torque, voltage, and current. The system will analyze historical data to identify patterns and predict temperature in advance, enabling proactive monitoring and predictive maintenance.

